\section{Introduction}

Using this method, we calculate from the resistance we are matching to
(generally $50\Omega$) to the destination impedance.

\section{Calculations for $Z_{br} < R_a$}

\begin{figure}[ht]
  \caption{L Match for $Z_{br} < R_a$}\label{LMatch1}
  \begin{center}
  \includesvg[scale=.25]{LMatch1}
  \end{center}
\end{figure}
Figure \ref{LMatch1} shows the basic L-Match if $Z_{br} < R_a$.  We
call this L-Match type 1.  There is a source with resistance $R_a$, a
matching network consisting of a mix of capacitors or inductors with
impedances $X_1$ and $X_2$, and a final impedance $Z_b$. $Z_b$ has
real and imaginary parts $Z_{br}$ and $Z_{bi}$. We assume a
non-complex source in this case.  The same math can be done for
complex sources, but it's more complicated.

To do this calculation, we start at $R_a$ and work our way to $Z_b$.
We do this in two stages:
\begin{itemize}
\item Calculate the value for $X_1$ so that it has the same real part
  as $Z_b$.  We call this $Z_1$.  It has a real part $Z_{1r}$ and an
  imaginary part $Z_{1i}$
\item Calculate the value of $X_2$ to take $Z_{1i}$ and move to $Z_{bi}$.
\end{itemize}
So the impedance value of $Z_1$ will be:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{R_a} + \frac{1}{j X_1}}
\end{dmath}
Now lets do a series of transformation to solve for $X_i$:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i} = \frac{j R_a X_1}{R_a + j X_1}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  (Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i})(R_a + j X_1) = j R_a X_1
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  R_a Z_{1r} + j X_1 Z_{1r} + j R_a Z_{1i} - Z_{1i} X_1 = j R_a X_1
\end{dmath}
Now solve for $X_1$:
\begin{dmath}
 j X_1 Z_{1r} - Z_{1i} X_1 - j R_a X_1 = - R_a Z_{1r} - j R_a Z_{1i} 
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
 X_1 = -R_a \frac{Z_{1r} + jZ_{1i}}{j Z_{1r} - Z_{1i} - j R_a}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
 X_1 = -R_a \frac{Z_{1r} + jZ_{1i}}{-Z_{1i} - j (R_a - Z_{1r})}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
 X_1 = R_a \frac{Z_{1r} + jZ_{1i}}{Z_{1i} + j (R_a - Z_{1r})}
\end{dmath}
Multiply the top and bottom of the right side by $Z_{1i} - j (R_a - Z_{1r})$
to get:
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = R_a \frac{-Z_{1r}Z_{1i} - Z_{1i}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
  + j R_a \frac{-Z_{1i}^2 + Z_{1r}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
Rework that a bit to get the signs in a little nicer place:
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = -R_a \frac{Z_{1r}Z_{1i} + Z_{1i}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
  - j R_a \frac{Z_{1i}^2 - Z_{1r}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac{-R_a Z_{1r}Z_{1i} - R_a Z_{1i}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
  + j \frac{-R_a Z_{1i}^2 + R_a Z_{1r}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac{-R_a Z_{1r}Z_{1i} - R_a^2 Z_{1i} + R_a Z_{1i}Z_{1r}}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
  + j \frac{-R_a Z_{1i}^2 + R_a^2 Z_{1r} - R_a Z_{1r}^2}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac{- R_a^2 Z_{1i}}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
  - j R_a\frac{Z_{1i}^2 - R_a Z_{1r} - Z_{1r}^2}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}

The imaginary part of this equation needs to be zero since the result
should be the real value for the impedance of $X_1$.  (Well, if it was
imaginary here, it would result in resistance when multiplying by $j$,
but we don't really want that either).  So solve that for zero:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i}^2 - R_a Z_{1r} - Z_{1r}^2 = 0
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i}^2 - Z_{1r}(R_a - Z_{1r}) = 0
\end{dmath}
or
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i} = \pm\sqrt{Z_{1r}(R_a - Z_{1r})}
\end{dmath}
We end up with two values, as we should, as there are two possible
solutions.  Then we plug into the left side of our main equation:
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = -R_a \frac{Z_{1r}Z_{1i} + Z_{1i}(R_a - Z_{1r})}{Z_{1i}^2 + (R_a - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
with both values of $Z_{1i}$ to get the two possible values of $X_1$.

Then to calculate $X_2$ in both cases is trivial, it's impedance should be
\begin{dmath}
  X_2 = - Z_{1i} - Z_{bi}
\end{dmath}
for both possible $Z_{1i}$ values.

Let's take an example.  Let's say you have $R_a = 50$ and $Z_b = 40 +
j 10$.  Plug into our equation:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i} = \sqrt{40(50 - 40)}
\end{dmath}
So $Z_{1i} = \pm 20$.  Now plug everything into our main equation:
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = -50 \frac{40(20) + 20(50 - 40)}{20^2 + (50 - 40)^2} = -100
\end{dmath}
and
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = -50 \frac{-40(-20) - 20(50 - 40)}{20^2 + (50 - 40)^2} = 100
\end{dmath}

In the first case we get an capacitor of value $X_1 = -100$ and
$Z_{1i} = 20$.  Now we need to move from $Z_{1i}$ to $Z_{bi}$ to
calculate $X_2$.  So:
\begin{dmath}
  X_2 = Z_{1i} - Z_{bi} = 20 - 10 = 10
\end{dmath}
so we need an inductor of that results in an impedance of $10$.

Working the other $Z_{1i} = -20$ value, we have an inductor $X_1 = 100$
an we do:
\begin{dmath}
  X_2 = Z_{1i} - Z_{bi} = -20 - 10 = -30
\end{dmath}
so we need an capacitor of that results in an impedance of $-30$.

This is basically the same procedure you would use on a Smith Chart,
but with direct calculation.

\section{Calculations for $Z_{br} > R_a$}

For $Z_{br} > R_a$ we have to work a little different.  If you try to
plug that into the previous equation, you will get negative values
inside the square root.  You might be able to use that to calculate
the imaginary part first, but I haven't looked at that.  It's easier
to flip the positions of $X_1$ and $X_2$ as shown in Figure
\ref{LMatch2}.  We call this L match type 2. Then we move $Z_b$ until
it's real impedance is $R_a$ and then calculate $X_2$.  And remember
that simplification for $R_a$ being real?  It no longer applies.  So
the math gets more complicated.  So lets change $R_a$ to $Z_a$ for a
more general case.

\begin{figure}[ht]
  \caption{L Match for $Z_{br} > Z_{ar}$}\label{LMatch2}
  \begin{center}
  \includesvg[scale=.25]{LMatch2}
  \end{center}
\end{figure}

\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i} = \frac{1}{\frac{1}{Z_{br} + j Z_{bi}} + \frac{1}{j X_1}}
\end{dmath}
Now lets do a series of transformation to solve for $X_i$:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i} = \frac{(Z_{br} + j Z_{bi}) j X_1}{Z_{br} + j Z_{bi} + j X_1}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i} = \frac{X_1 (- Z_{bi} + j Z_{br})}{Z_{br} + j(Z_{bi} + X_1)}
\end{dmath}
Now solve for $X_1$:
\begin{dmath}
  (Z_{1r} + j Z_{1i})(Z_{br} + j(Z_{bi} + X_1)) = X_1 (- Z_{bi} + j Z_{br})
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}(Z_{bi} + X_1) + j(Z_{br}Z_{1i} + Z_{1r}(Z_{bi} + X_1)) = X_1 (- Z_{bi} + j Z_{br})
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}X_1 - Z_{1i}Z_{bi} + j Z_{br}Z_{1i} + j Z_{1r}Z_{bi} + j Z_{1r}X_1 = -X_1Z_{bi} + j X_1Z_{br}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1(-Z_{1i} + j Z_{1r} + Z_{bi} - j Z_{br}) =
  - Z_{1r}Z_{br} + Z_{1i}Z_{bi} - j Z_{br}Z_{1i} - j Z_{1r}Z_{bi}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = -\frac{Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}Z_{bi} + j Z_{br}Z_{1i} + j Z_{1r}Z_{bi}}
              {-Z_{1i} + j Z_{1r} + Z_{bi} - j Z_{br}}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac{Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}Z_{bi} + j Z_{br}Z_{1i} + j Z_{1r}Z_{bi}}
             {Z_{1i} - j Z_{1r} - Z_{bi} + j Z_{br}}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac{(Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}Z_{bi}) + j(Z_{br}Z_{1i} + Z_{1r}Z_{bi})}
             {(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi}) + j(Z_{br} - Z_{1r})}
\end{dmath}
Multiply by the denominator with the $j$ part sign changed to get the
$j$ out of the denominator.
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac
  {\begin{matrix}
      (Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}Z_{bi})(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})\\
      + (Z_{br}Z_{1i} + Z_{1r}Z_{bi})(Z_{br} - Z_{1r})\\
      + j(Z_{1r}Z_{br} - Z_{1i}Z_{bi})(Z_{br} - Z_{1r})\\
      - j(Z_{br}Z_{1i} + Z_{1r}Z_{bi})(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})
  \end{matrix}}
  {(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})^2 + (Z_{br} - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac
  {\begin{matrix}
      Z_{1r}Z_{1i}Z_{br} - Z_{1r}Z_{br}Z_{bi} - Z_{1i}Z_{1i}Z_{bi} + Z_{1i}Z_{bi}Z_{bi}\\
      + Z_{br}Z_{br}Z_{1i} - Z_{1r}Z_{1i}Z_{br} + Z_{1r}Z_{br}Z_{bi} - Z_{1r}Z_{1r}Z_{bi})\\
      + j Z_{1r}Z_{br}Z_{br} - j Z_{1r}Z_{1r}Z_{br} - j Z_{1i}Z_{br}Z_{bi} + j Z_{1r}Z_{1i}Z_{bi}\\
      - j Z_{1i}Z_{li}Z_{br} + j Z_{1i}Z_{br}Z_{bi} - j Z_{1r}Z_{li}Z_{bi} + j Z_{1r}Z_{bi}Z_{bi}\\
  \end{matrix}}
  {(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})^2 + (Z_{br} - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_1 = \frac
  {\begin{matrix}
      - Z_{1i}^2Z_{bi} + Z_{1i}Z_{bi}^2\\
      + Z_{br}^2Z_{1i} - Z_{1r}^2Z_{bi}\\
      + j Z_{1r}Z_{br}^2 - j Z_{1r}^2Z_{br}\\
      - j Z_{1i}^2Z_{br} + j Z_{1r}Z_{bi}^2\\
  \end{matrix}}
  {(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})^2 + (Z_{br} - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
This is actually a more general formula than the one we did for
$Z_{br} < R_a$.  If you set $Z_{bi} = 0$ and $Z_{br} = R_a$ it will
reduce to the same formula.  Anyway, now split that into real and imaginary
parts:
\begin{dmath}
  X_{1r} = \frac{- Z_{1i}^2Z_{bi} + Z_{1i}Z_{bi}^2 + Z_{br}^2Z_{1i} - Z_{1r}^2Z_{bi}}
    {(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})^2 + (Z_{br} - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  X_{1i} = -j \frac{Z_{1r}Z_{br}^2 - Z_{1r}^2Z_{br} - Z_{1i}^2Z_{br} + Z_{1r}Z_{bi}^2}
  {(Z_{1i} - Z_{bi})^2 + (Z_{br} - Z_{1r})^2}
\end{dmath}
Like before, we want the imaginary part to be zero, so:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1r}Z_{br}^2 - Z_{1r}^2Z_{br} - Z_{1i}^2Z_{br} + Z_{1r}Z_{bi}^2 = 0
\end{dmath}
and solve for $Z_{1i}$:
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i}^2Z_{br} = Z_{1r}Z_{br}^2 - Z_{1r}^2Z_{br}  + Z_{1r}Z_{bi}^2
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i}^2 = \frac{Z_{1r}Z_{br}^2 - Z_{1r}^2Z_{br}  + Z_{1r}Z_{bi}^2}{Z_{br}}
\end{dmath}
\begin{dmath}
  Z_{1i} = \pm\sqrt{\frac{Z_{1r}Z_{br}^2 - Z_{1r}^2Z_{br}  + Z_{1r}Z_{bi}^2}{Z_{br}}}
\end{dmath}
which we can then use to calculate $X_1$.  Again, this is a more
general formula than the one we did for $Z_{br} < R_a$ and setting
$Z_{bi}$ to zero results in the same formula.

Then to calculate $X_2$ is again trivial, but it's flipped from the
type 1 calculation:
\begin{dmath}
  X_2 =  Z_{ai} - Z_{1i}
\end{dmath}
for both possible $Z_{1i}$ values.

You can use this to move from any impedance to any other.  You don't
have to use the calculations for $Z_{br} < R_a$, you can use this
instead, you just have to flip $Z_b$ and $Z_a$ since the matching
network will be flipped.

